We register `Cardinal.lift` as an initial segment embedding from `Cardinal.{u}` into `Cardinal.{max u v}`. This in particular implies it to be an order embedding via the new `InitialSeg.toOrderEmbedding`.

This unfortunately disables dot notation, but this didn't see much use for this function anyways.

In Lean 4, dot notation doesn't work with structures like this.

Ah right, you are bundling `Cardinal.lift`. What about keeping `Cardinal.lift` unbundled and instead having `Cardinal.liftInitialSeg` which would be `Cardinal.lift` bundled as an `InitialSeg`? This is what we have done in other places to preserve dot notation and pretty-printing, and places where we haven't done that are currently painful (eg `Multiset.card`)

I'm not a fan of having both bundled and unbundled versions of structures - surely the more you can infer about a function from just the type signature, the better?

It's important to note this is one of only two places in Mathlib we were using dot notation for `lift` to begin with.

> I'm not a fan of having both bundled and unbundled versions of structures - surely the more you can infer about a function from just the type signature, the better?

Well yes but in practice it only saves you one or two lemmas at the expense of your users needing to know whether the lemma holds true for a general bundled blah or just the specific one they have. Also, not applicable to your case, but there might not be a maximally general bundling.

Of course, I understand you can't always get the ultimate bundling defined at the get go. In fact, `lift` should also be a ring hom, and I think it'd be nice to make a bundled version for that at some point.

I do think `InitialSeg` is a different situation - being an initial segment embedding is *precisely* the characteristic property of `lift`! All of the order properties of `lift`, like `lift_succ`, `lift_iSup`, ..., and even some other properties like `lift_lift` or the TBA `lift_aleph`, follow from this fact.

I plan to generalize a lot of these results to general initial segment embeddings at some point, so it'd be nice not having to cast between the bundled version of `lift` and back in order to prove them for `lift`.
Please bring this discussion on Zulip
I'll do this tomorrow, I'm a bit tired at the moment.

It's a less-equal version of [`InitialSeg.init`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Order/InitialSeg.html#InitialSeg.init). But thinking about it, it might be better to restate this as `IsLowerSet (range f)`.
